"{\"uid\": \"windsorstar.com-news-local-news-fierce-intimidating-windsor-chef-team-canada-take-world-culinary-olympics-gold\", \"text\": \"You can save this article by registering for freehere. Orsign-inif you have an account.  It was an epic battle of blades, blow torches, and offset spatulas.  Subscribe now to read the latest news in your city and across Canada.  Subscribe now to read the latest news in your city and across Canada.  Create an account or sign in to continue with your reading experience.  Create an account or sign in to continue with your reading experience.  Windsor chef Adelina Sisti-DeBlasis is among the elite members of Culinary Team Canada, who recently returned from the World Culinary Olympics with gold and silver medals.  Every four years the world's best chefs don their aprons for the six-day competition in Stuttgart, Germany, where dreams of national pride and the perfect menu can rise and fall like an overbaked souffl\\u00e9.  The medals are another feather in the chef's toque for Sisti-DeBlasis, who was named National Chef of the Year in 2023 by the Culinary Federation of Canada.  This was her first trip to the Olympics of fine cuisine.  \\\"The competition is fierce. It's very intimidating at first,\\\" said Sisti-DeBlasis, also a hospitality, tourism and co-op teacher for the GreaterEssex CountyDistrict School Board.  \\\"So for my first, to bring home a gold is pretty exciting.\\\"  The International Exhibition of Culinary Art, better known as the World Culinary Olympics, ran Feb. 2 to 7. It is the largest international culinary arts event on the planet.  Team Canada won gold in the Restaurant of Nations category, which required teams to prepare a three-course meal for 110 guests. They also took silver in the Chef's Table category, preparing a seven-course menu for 14 people. \\u00a0Overall, Canada ranked sixth in the world out of 24 teams.  Sisti-DeBlasis was part of the Canadian squad's management team. Her jobs included communications, finance, administration, flavour critique, and recipe editor.  The vast Canuck-inspired menu included pine ice cream, Quebec First Nations spices, Newfoundland salt, sturgeon bacon, maple syrup, sea buckthorn berries, morel mushrooms, and bison.  \\\"We used the boreal forest as our backdrop,\\\" she said. \\\"There were very unique flavours that were reminiscent of Canada.\\\"  Overall, Finland won gold, Switzerland took silver, and the bronze went to Iceland. The national team from host country Germany finished behind Canada in ninth place.  \\\"Sixth overall is very impressive because I believe we are the only North American team to make the Top 10,\\\" said Sisti-DeBlasis. \\\"That feels fantastic.  \\\"It's been a decade or more for a national team to bring home a gold medal in Restaurant of Nations. It was very cool that that happened.\\\"  Sisti-DeBlasis said the European teams that consistently take the podium have a major advantage the Canadians do not - government funding.  \\\"It's hard to get to the podium with them,\\\" she said. \\\"But this year we were extremely close. That speaks volumes that Canada is a force to be reckoned with.\\\"  Unlike other countries, the Canadians have to do fundraisers and search for sponsors.  They also volunteer their time. And it's a lot of time. The team members travelled from across Canada for five-day practice runs, usually in Toronto, every eight weeks for the last four years.  Sisti-DeBlasis said she was grateful for the \\\"unwavering support\\\" of her family.  \\\"It's not easy to be away so often,\\\" she said. \\\"They were so encouraging and excited to see the awesome results of this four-year commitment.\\\"  For as long as Sisti-DeBlasis can remember, food has consumed her life.  \\\"Food is sustainability,\\\" she said. \\\"We can not survive without it. So it's important for us to kind of step back and be thankful and grateful for all the fruits that are around us.  \\\"Our lands are able to provide so much for us. As long as we treat it good, it will treat us better.\\\"  Sisti-DeBlasis was only seven years old when she created her first cookbook. It included the groundbreaking recipe for Lemon Spree, her crisp and complex combination of lemonade, 7 Up, and a lemon twist.  \\\"And just thinking I was a rockstar chef at seven years old.\\\"  That passion was fostered by her late mother and father, Immacolata and Ferruccio Sisti.  \\\"My mom was an excellent cook at the Ciociaro Club,\\\" said Sisti-DeBlasis. \\\"I loved watching her cook, sitting beside her and learning all the different techniques that she would do.  \\\"I caught the bug from her. Subsequently, dad was a fantastic cook after my mom passed away. Just wanting to experiment and do different and unique things.\\\"  She said her parents would have been \\\"completely elated\\\" to see how well Team Canada did.  \\\"That was my first stop when I arrived back from Germany, I went to the cemetery to show them some cool hardware,\\\" said Sisti-DeBlasis.  By bringing medals home to Windsor-Essex, and teaching young people to develop skills and dream big, she hopes to stir up the same passion in others that her parents inspired for her.  \\\"I love teaching and I love cooking,\\\" she said. \\\"I think the more involved you are in your community, the more you will get out of whatever it is that you do.  \\\"For me, it's a no-brainer. Food is passion. Passion is food.  \\\"Being able to get students excited about cooking, and maybe doing that for a living, is a win-win for everybody.\\\"  twilhelm@postmedia.com  Postmedia is committed to maintaining a lively but civil forum for discussion. Please keep comments relevant and respectful. Comments may take up to an hour to appear on the site. You will receive an email if there is a reply to your comment, an update to a thread you follow or if a user you follow comments. Visit ourCommunity Guidelinesfor more information.  365 Bloor Street East, Toronto, Ontario, M4W 3L4  \\u00a9 2025 Windsor Star, a division of Postmedia Network Inc. All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.  This website uses cookies to personalize your content (including ads), and allows us to analyze our traffic. Read more aboutcookies here. By continuing to use our site, you agree to ourTerms of UseandPrivacy Policy.  You can manage saved articles in your account.  and save up to 100 articles!  You can manage your saved articles in youraccountand clicking the X located at the bottom right of the article.\"}"